atus=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/678NyvGs8?url=http://www.lavieeco.com/documents_officiels/Recensement%20population.pdf |archivedate=23 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Name !! Geographic code !! Type !! House{{shy}}holds !! Population (2004) !! Foreign population !! Moroccan population !! Notes\n|-\n| Agdal || 231.01.01. || Arrondissement || 32740 || 144064 || 747 || 143317 ||\n|-\n| [[Fes Jdid|Mechouar Fes Jdid]] || 231.01.03. || Municipality || 6097 || 26078 || 83 || 25995 ||\n|-\n| [[Saiss]] || 231.01.05. || Arrondissement || 32990 || 156590 || 561 || 156029 ||\n|-\n| [[Fes el Bali|Fes-Medina]] || 231.01.07. || Arrondissement || 20088 || 91473 || 110 || 91363 ||\n|-\n| [[Jnan El Ouard]] || 231.01.09. || Arrondissement || 32618 || 174226 || 15 || 174211 ||\n|-\n| [[El Mariniyine]] || 231.01.11. || Arrondissement || 37958 || 163291 || 40 || 163251 ||\n|-\n| [[Oulad Tayeb]] || 231.81.01. || Rural commune || 3233 || 19144 || 3 || 19141 || 5056 residents live in the center, called [[Ouled Tayeb]]; 14088 residents live in rural areas.\n|-\n| [[Ain Bida]] || 231.81.03. || Rural commune || 1146 || 6854 || 0 || 6854 ||\n|-\n| [[Sidi Harazem]] || 231.81.05. || Rural commune || 982 || 5133 || 0 || 5133 || 3317 residents live in the center, called [[Skhinate]]; 1816 residents live in rural areas.\n|-\n|}\n\n== Landmarks ==\n===Medina of Fez===\nThe historic city of Fez consists of [[Fes el Bali|Fes el-Bali]], the original city founded by the [[Idrisid dynasty]] on both shores of the [[Oued Fes]] (River of Fez) in the late 8th and early 9th centuries, and the smaller [[Fes Jdid|Fez el-Jdid]], founded on higher ground to the west in the 13th century. It is distinct from Fez's now much larger Ville Nouvelle (new city) originally founded by the [[French protectorate in Morocco|French]]. Fes el-Bali is the site of the famous [[University of Al Quaraouiyine|Qarawiyyin University]] and the [[Zaouia Moulay Idriss II|Mausoleum of Moulay Idris II]], the most important religious and cultural sites, while Fez el-Jdid is the site of the enormous [[Dar al-Makhzen (Fez)|Royal Palace]], still used by the [[King of Morocco]] today. These two historic cities are linked together and are usually referred to together as the \"[[Medina quarter|medina]]\" of Fez, though this term is sometimes applied more restrictively to Fes el-Bali only.{{efn|''Medina'' is the Arabic word for \"city\", which in former French colonies in North Africa is also used to refer to the old part of a city, as the French largely generally built new cities (''Ville Nouvelles'') next to them and left the historic cities intact.}} Fez is becoming an increasingly popular tourist destination and many non-Moroccans are now restoring traditional houses ([[Moroccan riad|riads]] and dars) as second homes in the medina. Fez is also considered the cultural and spiritual capital of Morocco.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=F\u00e8s: Joyau de la civilisation islamique|last=Gaudio|first=Attilio|publisher=Les Presses de l'Unesco: Nouvelles \u00c9ditions Latines|year=1982|isbn=2723301591|location=Paris|pages=}}</ref>  In 1981, the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization ([[UNESCO]]) proclaimed ''Medina of Fez'' a [[World Heritage Site|World Cultural Heritage site]], as \"[they] include a considerable number of religious, civil and military monuments that brought about a multi-cultural society. This architecture is characterised by construction techniques and decoration developed over a period of more than ten centuries, and where local knowledge and skills are interwoven with diverse outside inspiration (Andalusian, Oriental and African). The Medina of Fez is considered as one of the most extensive and best conserved historic towns of the Arab-Muslim world.\"<ref>[https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/170 170]. ''UNESCO''. Retrieved January 22, 2018.</ref>{{wide image|Panorama of Fes (5364676502).jpg|1200px|align-cap=center|Panoramic view of the Old Medina}}\n\n===Places of worship===\n[[File:Inside of a mosque in Fes (5364764412).jpg|thumb|Inside the [[Zaouia Moulay Idriss II|Zawiya of Moulay Idriss II]], which contains the tomb of [[Idris II of Morocco|Idris II]].|alt=]]\nThere are numerous historic [[mosque]]s in the medina, some of which are part of a [[madrasa]] or [[Zawiya (institution)|zawiya]]. Among the oldest mosques still standing today are the highly prestigious [[University of al-Qarawiyyin|Mosque of al-Qarawiyyin]], founded in 857 (and subsequently expanded),<ref>[https://archnet.org/sites/1730 Jami' al-Qarawiyyin]. Retrieved January 22, 2018.</ref> the [[Al-Andalus Mosque (Fez)|Mosque of the Andalusians]] founded in to 859-860,<ref>[https://archnet.org/sites/1722 Jami' al-Andalusiyyin]. Retrieved January 22, 2018.</ref> the [[Bou Jeloud Mosque]] from the late 12th century<ref name=\":04\">{{Cite journal|last=Terrasse|first=Henri|date=1964|title=La mosqu\u00e9e almohade de Bou Jeloud \u00e0 F\u00e8s|url=|journal=Al-Andalus|volume=29|issue=2|pages=355\u2013363|via=}}</ref>, and possibly the Mosque of the [[Kasbah An-Nouar|Kasbah en-Nouar]] (which may have existed in the [[Almohad Caliphate|Almohad]] period but was likely rebuilt much later<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":03\">{{Cite book|title=F\u00e8s avant le protectorat: \u00e9tude \u00e9conomique et sociale d'une ville de l'occident musulman|last=Le Tourneau|first=Roger|publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Marocaine de Librairie et d'\u00c9dition|year=1949|isbn=|location=Casablanca|pages=}}</ref>). The very oldest mosques of the city, dating back to its first years, were the Mosque of the Sharifs (or Shurafa Mosque) and the Mosque of the Sheikhs (or [[al-Anouar Mosque]]); however, they no longer exist in their original form. The Mosque of the Sharifs was the burial site of [[Idris II of Morocco|Idris II]] and evolved into the [[Zaouia Moulay Idriss II|Zawiya of Moulay Idris II]] that exists today, while the al-Anouar Mosque has left only minor remnants.<ref name=\":03\" /> A number of mosques from the important [[Marinid dynasty|Marinid]] era, when [[Fes Jdid|Fes el-Jdid]] was created to be the capital of Morocco, include the [[Grand Mosque of Fes el-Jdid|Great Mosque of Fez el-Jdid]] from 1276, the [[Abu al-Hassan Mosque]] from 1341,<ref>[https://archnet.org/sites/1721 Abu al-Hassan Mosque]. Retrieved January 22, 2018.</ref> the [[Chrabliyine Mosque]] from 1342,<ref name=\"Ar2\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20131006045900/http://archnet.org/library/places/one-place.jsp?place_id=1675 Fez]. ''Archnet''. Retrieved January 23, 2018.</ref> the [[al-Hamra Mosque]] from around the same period (exact date unconfirmed),<ref name=\":022\">{{Cite book|title=L'architecture musulmane d'Occident|last=Mar\u00e7ais|first=Georges|publisher=Arts et m\u00e9tiers graphiques|year=1954|isbn=|location=Paris|pages=}}</ref> and the [[Bab Guissa Mosque]], also from the reign of [[Abu al-Hasan Ali ibn Othman|Abu al-Hasan]] (1331-1351) but modified in later centuries.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite book|title=Le Maroc andalou : \u00e0 la d\u00e9couverte d'un art de vivre|last=Touri|first=Abdelaziz|last2=Benaboud|first2=Mhammad|last3=Boujibar El-Khatib|first3=Na\u00efma|last4=Lakhdar|first4=Kamal|last5=Mezzine|first5=Mohamed|publisher=Minist\u00e8re des Affaires Culturelles du Royaume du Maroc & Museum With No Frontiers|year=2010|isbn=978-3902782311|edition=2|location=|pages=}}</ref> Other major mosques from the more recent Alaouite period are the [[Moulay Abdallah Mosque]], built in the early to mid-18th century with the tomb of Sultan [[Abdallah of Morocco|Moulay Abdallah]]<ref name=\":022\" />, and the [[R'cif Mosque]], built in the reign of [[Slimane of Morocco|Moulay Slimane]] (1793-1822).<ref>[https://archnet.org/sites/1731 Rasif Mosque]. Retrieved January 22, 2018.</ref> The Zawiya of Moulay Idriss II (previously mentioned) and the [[Sidi Ahmed al-Tijani Zawiya|Zawiya of Sidi Ahmed al-Tijani]] include mosque areas as well, as do several other prominent zawiyas in the city.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":03\" /> Elsewhere, the Jewish quarter ([[Mellah of Fez|Mellah]]) is the site of the 17th-century [[Ibn Danan Synagogue (Fes)|Ibn Danan Synagogue]].<ref name=\":01\" /> The Ville Nouvelle also includes many modern mosques.\n===Madrasas===\n[[File:Al-Attarine Madrasa YAC 2017.jpg|thumb|The interior view of [[Al-Attarine Madrasa]] built by the [[Marinid dynasty|Marinid]] sultan [[Abu al-Hasan Ali ibn Othman|Abu al-Hassan]] in 1323-1325.|alt=]]\nThe city has traditionally retained the influential position as a religious capital in the region, exemplified by the [[University of al-Qarawiyyin|Madrasa (or University) of al-Qarawiyyin]] which was established in 859 by [[Fatima al-Fihri]] originally as a mosque. The [[madrasa]] is the oldest existing and continually operating degree-awarding educational institution in the world according to [[UNESCO]] and [[Guinness World Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/3000/oldest-university|title=Oldest higher-learning institution, oldest university|website=Guinnessworldrecords.com|accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Medina of Fez|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/170|website=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|publisher=UNESCO|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref>\nDuring [[Marinid Sultanate|Marinid]] rule, Fez was also the political capital of the empire, partly due to the Sultan [[Abu Yaqub Yusuf an-Nasr|Abu Yaqub Yusuf]]'s intention to mitigate the tension between the [[ulama]]s in the old city.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} This led to the government devoting great attention to the construction of madrasas following the [[Maliki|Maliki orthodoxy]], resulting in the unprecedented prosperity of the city's religious institutions. The first madrasa built during the Marinid era was the [[Saffarin Madrasa]] in Fes el Bali by Sultan Abu Yusuf in 1271.<ref name=\":02\">Kubisch, Natascha (2011). \"Maghreb - Architecture\" in Hattstein, Markus and Delius, Peter (eds.) ''Islam: Art and Architecture''. h.f.ullmann.</ref>{{Rp|312}} Sultan [[Abu al-Hasan Ali ibn Othman|Abu al-Hassan]] was the most prolific patron of madrasa construction, completing the [[Al-Attarine Madrasa|Al-Attarine]], [[Mesbahiyya Madrasa|Mesbahiyya]] and [[Sahrij Madrasa]] in Fez alone, and several other madrasas as well in other cities such as [[Sal\u00e9]] and [[Meknes]]. His son [[Abu Inan Faris]] built the famed [[Bou Inania Madrasa]], and by the time of his death, every major city in the Marinid Empire had at least one madrasa.<ref name=\"Pe\" /> The library of the Madrasa of al-Qarawiyyin was also established under Marinid rule around 1350, which stores a large selection of valuable manuscripts dating back to the medieval era.<ref name=\":2\" /> The largest madrasa in the medina is [[Cherratine Madrasa]] commissioned by the [[Alaouite]] [[sultan]] [[Al-Rashid of Morocco|Al-Rashid]] in 1670, which is the only major non-Marinid foundation besides the Madrasa of al-Qarawiyyin.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121217001705/http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=2569 Shiratin Madrasa]. ''Archnet''. Retrieved January 23, 2018.</ref>\n\n===Fortifications===\n{{Main|Fortifications of Fez|Gates of Fez}}\n\n====City walls and gates====\n[[File:Fes-Morocco 59.jpg|alt=|thumb|250x250px|City walls of Fez (northern section).]]\nThe entire medina of Fez was heavily fortified with crenelated walls with watchtowers and gates, a pattern of urban planning which can be seen in Sal\u00e9 and [[Chellah]] as well.<ref name=\"Pe\">Penell, C.R. ''Morocco: From Empire to Independence''; Oneworld Publications, Oct 1, 2013. pp.66-67.</ref> City walls were placed into the current positions during the 11th century, under the Almoravid rule. During this period, the two formerly divided cities known as ''Madinat Fas'' and ''al-'Aliya'' were united under a single enclosure. The Almoravid fortifcations were later destroyed and then rebuilt by the Almohad dynasty in the 12th century, under Caliph [[Muhammad al-Nasir]].<ref name=\":03\" /> The oldest sections of the walls today thus date back to this time.<ref name=\":01\" /> These fortifications were restored and maintained by the Marinid dynasty from the 12th to 16th centuries, along with the founding of the royal citadel-city of Fes el-Jdid.<ref>[https://archnet.org/sites/2698 Fortifications of F\u00e8s]. ''Archnet''. Retrieved January 22, 2018.</ref> Construction of the new city's gates and towers sometimes employed the labour of Christian prisoners of war.<ref name=\"Pe\" />\n\nThe [[gates of Fez]], scattered along the circuit of walls, were guarded by the military detachments and shut at night.<ref name=\"Pe\" /> Some of the main gates have existed, in different forms, since the earliest years of the city.<ref name=\":03\" /> The oldest gates today, and historically the most important ones of the city, are [[Bab Mahrouk]] (in the west), [[Bab Guissa]] (in the northeast), and [[Bab Ftouh]] (in the southeast).<ref name=\":03\" /><ref name=\":01\" /> After the foundation of Fes Jdid by the Marinids in the 13th century, new walls and three new gates such as [[Bab al-Amer]] and [[Bab Semmarine]] were established along its perimeter.<ref>Meredith, Martin. (2014). ''Fortunes of Africa: A 5,000 Year History of Wealth, Greed and Endeavour''. Simon and Schuster.</ref><ref>Hakluyt Society, (1896). ''Works Issued by the Hakluyt Society'',\n p.592.</ref> Later, in modern times, the gates became more ceremonial rather than defensive structures, as reflected by the 1913 construction of the decorative [[Bab Bou Jeloud]] gate at the western entrance of Fes el-Bali by the [[French protectorate in Morocco|French colonial administration]].<ref name=\":01\" />[[File:Fes - Bab Chorfa.JPG|thumb|Bab Chorfa, the entrance gate to [[Kasbah An-Nouar]]. Open-air markets are held in front of the gate.|alt=]]\n\n==== Forts and kasbahs ====\nAlong with the city walls and gates, several forts were constructed along the defensive perimeters of the medina during the different time periods. The military watchtowers built in its early days during the [[Idrisid dynasty|Idrisid]] era were relatively small. However, the city rapidly developed as the military garrison center of the region during the Almoravid era, in which the military operations were commanded and carried out to other North African regions and Southern Europe to the north, and Senegal river to the south. Subsequently, it led to the construction of numerous forts, [[kasbah]]s, and towers for both garrison and defense. A \"kasbah\" in the context of [[Maghrebi]] region is the traditional military structure for fortification, military preparation, command and control. Some of them were occupied as well by citizens, certain tribal groups, and merchants. Throughout the history, 13 kasbahs were constructed surrounding the old city.<ref name=\"As\">[http://assabah.ma/70643.html <span class=\"ar\" style=\"font-size:1.15em;line-height:1.25em;font-family:&quot;Markazi Text&quot;,sans-serif;\">\u0646\u0641\u0627\u0626\u0633 \u0641\u0627\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u062a\u064a\u0642\u0629</span> : <span class=\"ar\" style=\"font-size:1.15em;line-height:1.25em;font-family:&quot;Markazi Text&quot;,sans-serif;\">\u0628\u0646\u0627\u0621</span> 13 <span class=\"ar\" style=\"font-size:1.15em;line-height:1.25em;font-family:&quot;Markazi Text&quot;,sans-serif;\">\u0642\u0635\u0628\u0629 \u0644\u0623\u063a\u0631\u0627\u0636 \u0639\u0633\u0643\u0631\u064a\u0629</span>]. ''Assabah''. Retrieved January 11, 2018.</ref> Among the most prominent among them is the [[Kasbah An-Nouar]], located at the western or north-western tip of Fes el-Bali, which dates back to the Almohad era but was restored and repurposed under the Alaouites.<ref name=\":03\" /> Today, it is an example of a kasbah serving as a residential district much like the rest of the medina, with its own neighborhood mosque. The Kasbah Bou Jeloud, which no longer exists as a kasbah today, was once the governor's residence and stood near Bab Bou Jeloud, south of the Kasbah an-Nouar.<ref name=\":03\" /> It too had its own mosque, known as the [[Bou Jeloud Mosque]]. Other kasbahs include the [[Kasbah Tamdert]], built by the [[Saadi dynasty|Saadis]] near Bab Ftouh, and the [[Kasbah Cherarda]], built by the [[Alaouite dynasty|Alaouite]] sultan [[Al-Rashid of Morocco|Moulay al-Rashid]] just north of Fes Jdid.<ref name=\":01\" /><ref name=\":03\" /> [[Kasbah Dar Debibagh]] is one of the newest kasbahs, built in 1729 during the Alaouite era at 2&nbsp;km from the city wall in a strategic position.<ref name=\"As\" /><ref>[https://archnet.org/sites/6376 Qasbah Dar Debibagh]. 'Archnet'' Retrieved January 22, 2018.''</ref> The Saadis also built a number of strong bastions in the late 16th century to assert their control over Fes, including notably the [[Borj Nord]] which is among the largest strictly military structures in the city and now refurbished as a military museum.<ref>[http://www.discoverislamicart.org/database_item.php?id=monument;ISL;ma;Mon01;12;ar&pageD=N <span class=\"ar\" style=\"font-size:1.15em;line-height:1.25em;font-family:&quot;Markazi Text&quot;,sans-serif;\" '>\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0631\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0645\u0627\u0644\u064a</span>]. ''Museum with no Frontiers''. Retrieved January 22, 2018.</ref> Its sister fort, [[Borj Sud]], is located on the hills to the south of the city.<ref name=\":03\" />\n\n===Tanneries===\n[[File:Clothes dyers in Fez, Morocco.jpg|thumb|Leather tanning in [[Chouara Tannery]].]]\nSince the inception of the city, [[tanning (leather)|tanning]] industry has been continually operating in the same fashion as it did in the early centuries. Today, the tanning industry in the city is considered one of the main tourist attractions. There are three tanneries in the city, largest among them is [[Chouara Tannery]] near the Saffarin Madrasa along the river, built in the 11th century. The tanneries are packed with the round stone wells filled with dye or white liquids for softening the hides. The leather goods produced in the tanneries are exported around the world.<ref>[https://archnet.org/sites/10359 Chouara Tannery]. ''Archnet''. Retrieved January 22, 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/photo-essays/2015-05-04/why-you-need-to-visit-fez-morocco-in-20-photos-travel-guide Why You Need to Visit Fez in 20 Photos]. ''Bloomberg''. Retrieved January 22, 2018.</ref><ref>Aziza Chaouni: Hybrid Urban Sutures: Filling in the Gaps in the Medina of Fez.\" Archit 96 no. 1 (2007): 58-63.</ref>\n\n===Tombs and mausoleums===\nLocated in the heart of Fes el Bali, the [[Zaouia Moulay Idriss II|Zaouia of Moulay Idriss II]] is a ''[[zaouia]]'' (a shrine and religious complex; also spelled ''zawiya''), dedicated to and contains the tomb of [[Idriss II|Idris II]] (or Moulay Idris II when including his [[sharif]]ian title) who is considered the main founder of the city of Fez.<ref name=\":0\">\"Fes\".'' Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica''. 2007. Britannica Concise Encyclopedia. 3 Mar. 2007</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=A history of the Maghrib in the Islamic period|last=Abun-Nasr|first=Jamil|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1987|isbn=0521337674|location=Cambridge|pages=}}</ref> Within the medina quarter, there exists as well the [[Sidi Ahmed al-Tijani Zawiya|Zaouia of Sidi Ahmed al-Tijani]], which commemorates Sidi Ahmed al-Tijani, the founder of [[Tijaniyyah]] [[tariqa]] from the 18th century.<ref>[https://archnet.org/sites/1737 Sidi Ahmed al-Tijani Zawiya]. ''Archnet''. Retrieved January 22, 2018.</ref> To the north, there are [[Marinid Tombs]] built during the 14th century as a necropolis for the [[Marinid Sultanate|Marinid sultans]].<ref name=\":01\">{{Cite book|title=F\u00e8s: La ville essentielle|last=M\u00e9talsi|first=Mohamed|publisher=ACR \u00c9dition Internationale|year=2003|isbn=978-2867701528|location=Paris|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThe old city also has several major historic cemeteries which existed outside the main city gates, namely the cemeteries of [[Bab Ftouh]] (the most significant), [[Bab Mahrouk]], and [[Bab Guissa]]. Some of these cemeteries include [[Marabout|marabouts]] or domed structures containing the tombs of local [[Wali|Muslim saints]] (often considered [[Sufism|Sufis]]). One of the most important ones is the Marabout of [[Ali ibn Harzihim|Sidi Harazem]] in the Bab Ftouh Cemetery.<ref name=\":03\" />\n\n===Gardens===\nThe [[Jnan Sbil Gardens|Jnane Sbile Garden]] was created as a royal park and garden in the 19th century by [[Sultan]] [[Hassan I of Morocco|Moulay Hassan I]] (ruled 1873-1894) between Fes el-Jdid and Fes el-Bali.<ref name=\"M\u00e9talsi 2003\">{{Cite book|last=M\u00e9talsi|first=Mohamed|title=F\u00e8s: La ville essentielle|publisher=ACR \u00c9dition Internationale|year=2003|isbn=978-2867701528|location=Paris|pages=}}</ref>{{Rp|296}}<ref name=\":05\">{{Cite book|last=Le Tourneau|first=Roger|title=F\u00e8s avant le protectorat: \u00e9tude \u00e9conomique et sociale d'une ville de l'occident musulman|publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Marocaine de Librairie et d'\u00c9dition|year=1949|isbn=|location=Casablanca|pages=}}</ref>{{Rp|100}} Today it is the oldest garden of Fes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://morocco.falktime.com/jnane-sbile-garden/|title=Jnane Sbile or Bab Bou Jeloud garden in Fez|date=2018-07-09|website=Morocco.FalkTime|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-09}}</ref>\n\n===Residences===\n[[File:Kings palace in Fes (5364773212).jpg|thumb|Gates of the Alaouite Royal Palace ([[Dar al-Makhzen (Fez)|Dar al-Makhzen]]).]]\nThe old city of Fez includes more than a hundred ''funduq''s or ''foundouk''s (traditional inns, like urban [[Caravanserai|caravanserais]]) for visiting merchants and travelers alike. Among the prominent funduqs are the [[Funduq al-Najjariyyin]], which was built in the 18th century by Amin Adiyil to provide accommodation and storage for merchants.<ref>[https://archnet.org/sites/1397 Funduq al-Najjariyyin]. ''Archnet''. Retrieved January 22, 2018.</ref> Older funduqs include [[Funduq Achich]] from the 16th century.<ref>[https://archnet.org/sites/15585 Fondouk Achich]. ''Archnet''. Retrieved January 22, 2018.</ref> Many old private residences have also survived to this day, in various states of conservation. One type of house known, centered around an internal courtyard, is known as a ''[[Moroccan riad|riad]]''.<ref name=\":01\" /> Such private houses include the Dar al-Alami<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archnet.org/sites/2555|title=Alami House|website=Archnet|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>, the Dar Saada (now a restautant), Dar 'Adiyil, Dar Belghazi, and others.<ref name=\":01\" /> Larger and richer mansions, such as the Dar Mnebbhi, Dar Moqri, and Palais Jama\u00ef, have also been preserved.<ref name=\":01\" /> Numerous funduqs, palaces, and riads are now utilized as hotels for the tourism industry. Some of them are also been converted into tourist attractions, such as the Funduq al-Najjariyyin which is now the Nejjarine Museum of Wooden Arts & Crafts.<ref name=\":122\">{{Cite book|title=A practical guide to Islamic Monuments in Morocco|last=Parker|first=Richard|publisher=The Baraka Press|year=1981|isbn=|location=Charlottesville, VA|pages=}}</ref> The lavish former mansion of the [[Thami El Glaoui|Glaoui]] clan, known as the Dar Glaoui, is also partly open to visitors but still privately owned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lonelyplanet.com/morocco/fez/attractions/palais-glaoui/a/poi-sig/1552465/355510|title=Palais Glaoui {{!}} Fez, Morocco Attractions|website=www.lonelyplanet.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> The Palais Jama\u00ef is now a hotel.<ref name=\":01\" />\n\nAs a former administrative seat, the city contains several palaces as well. [[Dar Batha]] is a former palace completed in 1897 by the Alaouite Sultan [[Abdelaziz of Morocco|Moulay Abdelaziz]] and turned into a museum in 1915 with around 6,000 pieces.<ref>[http://www.minculture.gov.ma/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=665%3A2010-01-20-13-51-39&catid=67&Itemid=133#\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0637\u062d\u0627\u0621 <span class=\"ar\" style=\"font-size:1.15em;line-height:1.25em;font-family:&quot;Markazi Text&quot;,sans-serif;\" '>\u0645\u062f\u064a\u0646\u0629 \u0641\u0627\u0633</span>]. ''Ministry of Culture''. Retrieved January 22, 2018.</ref> A large area of Fes el-Jdid is also taken up by the 80 hectare Royal Palace, or [[Dar al-Makhzen (Fez)|Dar al-Makhzen]], whose new ornate gates (built in 1969-71) are renowned but whose grounds are not open to the public.<ref name=\":122\" />\n{{clear}}\n== Education ==\n[[File:Var 132.jpg|thumb|right|[[University of Al Quaraouiyine]].]]\n\n===Universities===\n{{Main|University of Al Quaraouiyine}}\nThe [[University of Al Quaraouiyine]] is the oldest continually-operating university in the world.<ref>[[Guinness World Records]], [http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/3000/oldest-university Oldest University]</ref> The al-Karaouine mosque was founded by [[Fatima al-Fihri]] in 859 with an associated school, or [[madrasa]], which subsequently became one of the leading spiritual and educational centers of the historic [[Muslim world]].<ref>UNESCO, [https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/170 World Heritage Listing for Medina of Fez.]</ref> It became a state university in 1963, and remains an important institution of learning today.<ref>Larbi Arbaoui, [http://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2012/10/59056/al-karaouin-of-fez-the-oldest-university-in-the-world/ Al Karaouin of Fez: The Oldest University in the World], Morocco World News, 2 October 2012.</ref>\n\n[[Sidi Mohamed Ben Abdellah University]] is a public university that was founded in 1975 and has two primary campuses in the city (Dhar El Mehraz and Sais).\n\n== Transport ==\n[[File:Gare de Fes 2011.jpg|thumb|Gare de Fes, train station in the modern urban area of Fez.]]\nThe city is served by [[Fes-Sa\u00efss Airport|Sa\u00efss Airport]]. It also has an [[ONCF]] train station with lines east to [[Oujda]] and west to [[Tangier]] and [[Casablanca]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oncf.ma/Fr/index.aspx?md=199&rb=396 |title=::.. Oncf ..:: |publisher=Oncf.ma |accessdate=2009-05-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228041222/http://www.oncf.ma/Fr/index.aspx?md=199&rb=396 |archivedate=2009-02-28 }}</ref>\n\n== Sport ==\nFez has two [[association football|football]] teams, [[MAS Fez]] (F\u00e9s Maghrebi) and [[Wydad de F\u00e8s]] (WAF). They both play in the [[Botola]] the highest tier of the Moroccan football system and play their home matches at the 45,000 seat [[Complexe Sportif de F\u00e8s]] stadium.\n\nThe [[MAS Fez basketball team]] competes in the [[Nationale 1]], Morocco's top basketball division.\n\n== International relations ==\n{{Main|List_of_twin_towns_and_sister_cities_in_Africa#Morocco|l1=List of twin towns and sister cities in Morocco}}\n\n=== Twin towns&nbsp;\u2014 sister cities ===\n{{More citations needed section|date=January 2018}}\nFez is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n{{columns-list|colwidth=35em|\n\n* {{flagicon|BEL}} [[Antwerp]], Belgium, since 2000\n* {{flagicon|BAN}} [[Dhaka]], Bangladesh, since 1976\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Montpellier]], France, since 1961\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Strasbourg]], France, since 1961\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Florence]], Italy, since 1961\n*{{flagicon|TUN}} [[Kairouan]], [[Tunisia]], since 1965\n*{{flagicon|ALG}} [[Tlemcen]], [[Algeria]], since 1969\n*{{flagicon|SEN}} [[Saint-Louis, Senegal|Saint Louis]], Senegal, since 1979\n*{{flagicon|ESP}} [[C\u00f3rdoba, Andalusia]], Spain, since 1982\n*{{flagicon|PLE}} [[East Jerusalem]], [[Palestinian territories]]  since 1982\n*{{flagicon|TUR}} [[\u0130zmir]], Turkey, since 1995<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.izmir-yerelgundem21.org.tr/kardes.htm| title = Sister cities of \u0130zmir (1/7)|author=|website=Izmir-yerelgundem21.org.tr| accessdate=2008-11-01| language=Turkish}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|BFA}} [[Bobo-Dioulasso]], Burkina Faso, since 2003\n*{{flagicon|KOR}} [[Suwon]], South Korea, since 2003\n*{{flagicon|POR}} [[Coimbra]], Portugal<ref name=\"Coimbra Twinning\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cm-coimbra.pt/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=62&Itemid=128|title=Acordos de Gemina\u00e7\u00e3o|website=Cm-coimbra.pt |language=Portuguese|accessdate=2009-06-25}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|PAK}} [[Lahore]], Pakistan\n*{{flagicon|PAK}} [[Multan]], Pakistan\n*{{flagicon|MEX}} [[Puebla City]], Mexico\n}}\n\n=== Partnerships ===\n*{{flagicon|POL}} [[Krak\u00f3w]] in [[Poland]] <small>''(since 1985)''<ref name=\"Krak\u00f3w partnerships\">{{cite web|url=http://www.krakow.pl/otwarty_na_swiat/2531,kat,0,5,miasta_partnerskie.html|title=Krak\u00f3w - Miasta Partnerskie|accessdate = 2013-08-10|work=Miejska Platforma Internetowa Magiczny Krak\u00f3w|language=Polish|trans-title=Krak\u00f3w -Partnership Cities|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130702010825/http://www.krakow.pl/otwarty_na_swiat/2531,kat,0,5,miasta_partnerskie.html|archivedate=2013-07-02}}</ref></small>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Treaty of Fez]]\n* [[Timeline of Fez#Bibliography|Bibliography of the history of Fez]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |first=Roger |last=Le Tourneau |translator=Besse Clement |title=Fez in the Age of the Marinides |publisher=Oklahoma University |orig-year=1961 |date=1974 |isbn=0-8061-1198-4 }}\n* {{cite book |first=Julian |last=Vigo |date=2006 |chapter=The Renovation of Fes' ''medina qdima'' and the (re)Creation of the Traditional |title=Writing the City, Transforming the City |location=New Delhi |publisher=Katha |pages=44\u201358 }}\n* {{cite web |title=Place Lalla Yeddouna A Neighborhood in the Medina of Fez, Morocco: International open project competition in two phases |url=http://www.projectcompetition-fez.com/ }} Announced in September 2010 in collaboration with the Union International des Architectes (UIA) and the Millennium Challenge Corporation (MCC), to renew the area and upgrade the living and working standards of the artisans in the medina. The approach of the project is probably one of the most ambitious for an Arab medina and therefore of exemplary character. The open international project was won by the London-based architecture practice [[Michel Mossessian|Mossessian & Partners]].\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Fes}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Fez}}\n{{Wikitionary|Fez}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051023042538/http://www.portaildefes.ma/ Official government website of the city]\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.islamicarchitecturedatabase.org/ircica/index2.php?page=Country&id=34 |title=Fez |work=Islamic Cultural Heritage Database |publisher=Organization of Islamic Cooperation, Research Centre for Islamic History, Art and Culture |location=Istanbul |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130427083717/http://www.islamicarchitecturedatabase.org/ircica/index2.php?page=Country&id=34 |archivedate=2013-04-27 }}\n*{{cite web|author=ArchNet.org |publisher=MIT School of Architecture and Planning |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts, USA |url=http://archnet.org/library/places/one-place.jsp?place_id=1675 |title=Fez |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006045900/http://archnet.org/library/places/one-place.jsp?place_id=1675 |archivedate=2013-10-06 }}\n\n<br />\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Capital of Islamic Culture]]\n|before=[[Aleppo]]\n|after=[[Alexandria]], [[Djibouti]], [[Lahore]]\n|years=2007}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Fes}}\n{{F\u00e8s-Mekn\u00e8s}}\n{{Prefectures and provinces of Morocco}}\n{{World Heritage Sites in Morocco}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Fez, Morocco| ]]\n[[Category:Prefecturial capitals in Morocco]]\n[[Category:Regional capitals in Morocco]]\n[[Category:789 establishments]]\n[[Category:8th-century establishments in Africa]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 8th century]]\n[[Category:Burial sites of the Idrisid dynasty]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Fes||FES (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the Table at Infobox Settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|name          = Fez\n|native_name = {{lang|ar|\u0641\u0627\u0633}}<br>Fas / \u2d3c\u2d30\u2d59<br>F\u00e8s\n| settlement_type = [[List of cities in Morocco|City]]\n|image_skyline          = Fezmedinafinal.jpg\n|imagesize              = 275px\n|image_caption          = '''Clockwise from top:'''<br> View of [[Fes el Bali]], [[Bou Inania Madrasa]], [[University of Al Quaraouiyine]], street view, [[Zaouia Moulay Idriss II]], [[Chouara Tannery]], [[Bab Bou Jeloud]]\n|image_flag             =\n|flag_size              =100px\n|image_seal             =\n|seal_size              =\n|image_shield           =\n|shield_size            =\n|image_blank_emblem     =\n|blank_emblem_type      =\n|blank_emblem_size      =\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_map              =\n|mapsize                =\n|map_caption            =\n|image_map1             =\n|mapsize1               =\n|map_caption1           =\n|pushpin_map            = Morocco#Africa\n|pushpin_label_position = left\n|pushpin_relief           = yes\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location of Fez within Morocco\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|coordinates            = {{coord|34|2|N|5|0|W|region:MA|display=inline,title}}\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Morocco}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Regions of Morocco|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[F\u00e8s-Mekn\u00e8s]]\n<!-- Politics ----------------->\n|established_title      =Founded<!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       =789\n|established_title2     =  <!-- Incorporated (town) -->\n|est